<% content_for :sidebar_meat do %>
	<strong><%= link_to "Continue to collection &rarr;".html_safe, edit_collection_path(@importer.collection), class: "button tiny c-secondary" %></strong>
<% end %>

<h2>Import successful: <%= pluralize(@saved_records.count, 'record') %> imported</h2><br><br>
<div class="row">
	<div class="small-10 columns indented">
		<p class="emphasis-box"><strong>Please review the example records below.</strong> If anything looks wrong, <%= link_to "view the new collection", edit_collection_path(@importer.collection), class: "normal-link" %> and delete it on that screen. Then, modify your Excel file and try the import again. Note that you can modify individual term records from the main search screen to fix any minor errors.</p><br>
	</div>
</div>

<div class="row">
	<div class="small-10 columns emphasis-box indented">
		<h3>First few records created:</h3>
		<table class="records-table">
			<thead>
				<tr>
					<% set_columns.each do |lang| %>
						<th class="lang-column" width="<%= 60 / set_columns.length %>%"><%= lang.capitalize %></th>
					<% end %>
					<th class="source-column">Source</th>
					<th class="domain-column">Domain</th>
					<th class="expander-column"></th>
				</tr>
			</thead>
			<tbody class="no-links">
				<%= render @saved_records.limit(5) %>
			</tbody>
		</table>
		<p>The next step is to name your collection of newly imported term records. If something looks wrong above, you can delete the collection on the next screen.</p>
		<%= link_to "Continue to collection", edit_collection_path(@importer.collection), class: "button small" %>
	</div>
</div>